This paper deals with combinatorial and geometric properties of sets in $\mathbb{R}^d$, which is a typical topic in computational geometry (cs.CG). The analysis of the number of permutations involves counting techniques and asymptotic bounds, which are also common in discrete mathematics (cs.DM) and theoretical computer science (cs.CC). The use of logarithmic factors suggests that the authors may have employed data structures or algorithms that exploit the sparsity of the problem, which is a characteristic of computational geometry (cs.DS). Finally, the study of geometric permutations involves the analysis of the combinatorial structure of sets, which is related to the field of graph theory (cs.GT).
